title: For Sale:  Fraud Alert!  Scammers!! Important...
postcontent:
I normally dont put up a "rant " like this, but I have been really bothered by the increased scamming activity online lately.  Right now, there are a lot of scams on Armslist.  I'm sure they are doing their best here on the site to take them down as fast as possible, but it is still very important to be careful.  When I logged on this morning and searched under the "over and under" section, 8 of the first 10 posts of the day were clearly scams.  This is a crazy amount and makes it hard for people to actually find a "real seller" to buy a gun.

Things to look for in identifing a scam:

1) Price - they are almost always way too cheap to be a real deal.  If a gun is listed for 50% of its value, its probably a scam.

2) Listing the location twice - I have noticed that almost all the scams will have the location listed twice.  For example, it might say "LaCrosse, LaCrosse, Wisconsin", or "Madison, Madison, Wisconsin" or even "Wisconsin, Wisconsin".  This does not always mean it is a scam, but it is a large red flag.

3) Phone contact - Always attempt to make phone contact with someone.  Scammers love to hide behind an email.  Also, dont give your phone number to them, request the seller give theirs to you.  A true seller will have no problem with this, scammers will not usually give you a number.

4) If ever possible, meet face to face - This is the obvious way to avoid any fraud.

title: For Sale/Trade:  160gr 30 cal bullet mold AND 580 cast bullets
postcontent:
Lee TL312-160-2r bullet mold

With mold, you get 582 bullets. These bullets were cast from pure clip on wheel weight lead and quenched after casting and powder coating for a harder bullet. This is a project that got shut down before it even started. This mold design is intended for 7.62x39 but is used by many for use in other calibers. This bullet was not a keeper for use in my 300 blackout so Im just sticking with a heavy 230 grain bullet.

The mold casts pure clip on wheel weight alloy  at .3105-.311". I have casted about 700 bullets with the mold.

Bullets included with this mold:

260 As cast, water dropped .3105-.311 diameter

230 with 2 coats of powdercoat, water dropped after baking. Bullets were sized to .309 between coats for a final diameter of ~ .311" give or take .0005"

92 bullets with just one layer of powder coat and no sizing. these are .312-.313"

title: For Sale/Trade:  Enfield #5 Jungle Carbine .303 Fazakerly 1946  The Real Deal number five #5
postcontent: Stock/frame/magazine matched rifle.  It is a True Jungle Carbine, not a put-together from a number one or number four.  Notice the "lightened" bolt etc. - research a bit so you don't get screwed buying one that has been converted! [I just did a search on "armslist" - most if not all are "made-up" jungle carbines!]  I have used it for my "Bad Weather" Deer Rifle for about the last 20 years or so.  It was packed with cosmoline when I first got it - I think it's about gone now!  It has an import stamp just behind the flash hider on the barrel, and I think this one made it through to the US from Maylasia, which was sold surplus from the UK after WWII.  The bluing is in pretty decent shape, but the stock finish is a bit scratched up - nothing deep.  It should refinish nicely - I don't sand the stocks on my guns, as I like to keep them as original as possible.  I think the Mayays kept them in a gymnasium sized room and tossed them from one side to the other every two or three years or so, accounting for the stock scratches.  It's in pretty nice shape otherwise.  The bore is excellent.  I have never had a bit of trouble with the "wandering zero".  I find it to be very accurate myself, and my Hornady 150 grain loads print 3" high at 100 yards with the open battle peep sight, and a nice, tight cluster.  I managed to shoot my 2nd largest buck with this rifle - a running shot at ~ 7 seconds after he came running over a hill, and was about to disappear over the next one!  I was able to shoulder quick, acquire the sight picture and shoot within that 7 seconds.  I also have a spare magazine (Savage marked) for an extra $50, and if you need dies, reloadable brass and bullets, that's available too.  If it sells, I'll miss it - I think it is about the perfect hunting rifle, more or less like the "new" Ruger Scout rifle, only with history!  Keep it in good shape, and the value will only go up!  Ignore the "Springfield" Manufacturing listing.  They don't have a listing for Military Rifles - no Enfield or Fazakerly etc.
